column168: During loading there was no signs of product leaking.  Driver moved to the customer scale on site and noticed the turpentine smell and then saw a leak coming from the bottom forward section of the insulation through a weep hole.  Driver moved it to the customer containment area on site.  We formulated a game plan with the shipper to transfer it in to a new trailer.  We also brought in a response team to 'diaper' the trailer in the interim to help contain it.  The transload was successful and the trailer stopped leaking and was cleaned and put on the train back to Chicago.
column169: The trailer just arrived in Chicago this week.  It has not been inspected yet but we are confident this will be a barrel leak.  I do not anticipate that the leak is due to corrosion.  I suspect this is due to a crack in a specific spot where the barrel recieves the most impact pressure when they are lifted on and off the train.  There is a reinforcement kit that will be installed when / if that is the case.  I will update this form once we have confirmation on the root cause - corrective actions.

column168: 08/01/2023, at 10:52 hours, A FRA inspector in the CSXT Manville yard discovered the SHPX222886, a residue tank car of Waste Flammable Liquid, having a vapor release from the top of the car. The rail car was isolated and the shipper, GEOCYCLE, was notified via the waybill’s emergency contact number (877-818-0087).  MEI, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the car was releasing product vapor due to a faulty vacuum relief valve (VRV). Contractor personnel removed the faulty VRV and installed a pipe plug to stop the release. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative- Marvin Sparks (843-826-1746, marvin.sparks@geocycle.com). The car was held at this location pending further repair and qualification by a certified mobile repair unit or receipt of One Time Move Approval from the FRA.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal UPH experienced a : UN1819 Sodium Aluminate release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-cup of product released impacting a 1' x 1' area of the trailer floor and a 1' x 1' area of the dock floor due to a puncture. The product was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one. Absorbents and neutralizer were deployed to clean the impacted areas. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized along with all waste into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: 1. X-2023080558 SequenceEvent: Package was processed and being delivered to Outbounds, Load Area 1. A few minutes later, manager explained to me box was leaking powder. Box was not leaking beforehand. Probable cause of leakage could be mishandling of package by package handler. No damages to outer packaging.  Cleaned up area by sweeping up powder substance into the QA bin with the damaged hazmat in bin as well. DescribePack: Lid of Inner packaging was loose and seemed to be the source of leakage. Location of the loose end was the back of the package. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Checked to see if all openings were closed and package was standing upright.   2. X-2023080636 SequenceEvent: Package was found in outbounds by management leaking the substance. DOT hazmat label was located on the package and QA was called. QA contained spill and placed package in hazmat tote. DescribePack: Package had loose lid causing contents to spill out DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Substance was contained and package was placed in hazmat tote

column168: SequenceEvent: The outer pkg contained 4 plastic jugs of chemical drain cleaner.  The jugs had screw-on caps.  At some point during the pkg's shipment the vibration of transit caused the jugs' screw-on caps to loosen.  3 of the jugs' caps were only slightly loose while the 4th jug's cap was found completely off the jug. Chemical odor and pkg dampness prompted inspection at the delivery station.  The pkg was placed in a plastic tub when first discovered and was sent to the station's QA area for eventual inspection and processing. DescribePack: Again, vessels that employ screw-on caps are prone to having the caps loosen from the vibration of transit alone.  3 of the 4 jugs' caps were found to be slightly loose - the 4th jug's cap was completely off. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The caps on the jugs were tightened, the jugs were wiped down with paper towels, and contaminated cardboard was contained in a plastic tub.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: XPO Logistics terminal XWO experienced a release from a 2950-pound battery. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-gallons of battery acid released impacting multiple areas of concrete to include a 10' x 10' and 20' x 10' areas, a 40' x 1' area of the ramp and a 5' x 5' area where the battery was sitting. The battery tipped over in transit causing 6 of the caps to be lost, resulting in a release. Terminal personnel removed the battery from the trailer to a dock area, which resulted in acid being released to multiple areas. The crew worked the absorbents deployed by XPO into the impacted areas and collected them into drums. The areas were then neutralized with sodium bicarb. All impacted absorbents and cleanup debris were placed into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The damaged battery was up righted and secured to a new pallet, with poly sheeting taped over it to prevent further release. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.
column172: Box, wood or fiberboard not specified

column168: XPO Logistics terminal NCH experienced a UN3267 Sikadur 52 Part B release from (3) 1-gallon metal pails. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 3-gallons of product released to an 8' x 2' area of the trailer floor and an 8' x 8' area of the concrete lot below the trailer. The crew advised the lids of the pails were crushed due to improper loading causing the release. Oil Gator was deployed and worked into the impacted areas. Once complete, the areas were pH strip tested to confirm neutralization. All waste was then containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XLL experienced a release of UN1760 NAG-75 from (4) 5-gallon poly pails and non-regulated iShine from (3) 5-gallon poly pails. The damaged pails of non-regulated iShine containerized into a 55-gallon metal drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: First Call Environmental was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 3ft-by-2ft area of the concrete dock floor and an 8ft-by-6ft area of the trailer floor and estimated that three (3) gallons of material was released. First Call Environmental personnel removed 29 boxes that contained two (2) 1-gallon plastic jugs that were impacted by the released material. The non-damaged boxes (a total 67 boxes) were restacked and shipped onto the consignee. First Call Environmental personnel deployed a neutralizer to the impacted areas and First Call Environmental personnel recovered the spent material and containerized it into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The impacted cardboard and plastic jugs were placed into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The generated waste was staged onsite in a secure location at the terminal prior to the contractor demobilization.  The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

column168: On August 18, 2023, at 0239 ET, XPO Logistics terminal LTU suffered a cargo related release of UN3149 “AcidiShine” to the trailer floor and asphalt lot below from a 55-gallon poly drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. On August 18, 2023, at 0530 ET, contractors arrived onsite. Crew confirmed one 55-gallon poly drum of UN3149 “AcidiShine” released due to a pallet nail puncture. Approximately 30-gallons released to a 5’ x 30’ area of the trailer floor and a 10’ x 5’ area of the asphalt lot below. The impacted surfaces and debris were neutralized with a vinegar solution and confirmed neutral with pH test strips. Absorbents were then deployed and worked into the impacted areas. The empty damaged drum was containerized into an 85-gallon vented poly drum. All impacted absorbents and cleanup debris were collected into a 55-gallon vented poly drum. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

The impacted absorbents, impacted cardboard, and rags were collected and containerized into a supersack. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: While loading an outbound trailer of totes at Veolia's 10-day facility in Port Allen, LA a forklift punctured the IBC. The forks of the lift were extending approximately 3-4 inches beyond the underneath of the IBC and while repositioning the tote the fork made contact with another tote behind it, resulting in a ~3" gash at the bottom corner of the container. The tote began leaking rapidly and spilled ~150 gallons within a 10 minute span. The material flooded the back of the box van and the surrounding concrete of the dock area. The Veolia team quickly began blocking off the storm drain located in the dock area with spill pads and oil dry, as well as blocking off the back of the trailer to slow the pace of the material leaking out the trailer. The spill was promptly cleaned up and absorbent material was containerized. The remaining material in the damaged tote was transferred into a new container.
column169: Additional training on tote-specific handling with a forklift will help prevent any further incidents. Another process related suggestion would be to identify opportunities where our team could minimize the need to move the containers as much as possible, for example setting the material up to be delivered directly to the disposal facility when feasible instead of offloading and loading again at the 10-Day facility.

column42: BUTADIENES, STABILIZED OR BUTADIENES AND HYDROCARBON MIXTURE, STABILIZED CONTAINING MORE THAN 40% BUTADIENES
column168: I received a call that there was an odor emitting from a residue Butadiene car in Livonia LA. The car was isolated and discovered that the vapor valve was a quarter turn in the open position with the plug less than tool tight. The valve was closed, and the plug properly tightened, and the odor subsided. No further action was taken and the car release back into transportation.

Container HGIU 516245 (load-mixed hazmat) released 0.5 gallons of liquid from the bottom of the container to the ground in the Lathrop yard. 3 out of 12 5-gallon pails of "Zep Morado Super Clean", UN3266 Corrosive Liquid, Basic, Inorganic, N.O.S. (Sodium Thiophosphate) were damaged and released. 1 pail completely released, and the other 2 pails each released 1-gallon, with a total of 7-gallons released. Cause of the release was shifted load and no blocking and bracing.

column168: SequenceEvent: Package was picked up from the shipper, and when the truck was opened to be unloaded there was a damaged hazmat leaking on the floor of the truck. When inspecting the package, the Ethanol, was packaged in plastic containers which then was placed in cardboard boxes. One of the four plastic containers had caved in on itself where it leaked on the bottom of the box making the other three wet along with the bottom of the box.  The other three were not leaking at all. DescribePack: I would say the heat made the plastic container cave in on itself causing it to dent and leak. DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: package was moved to the hazmat cage; bay doors open, and fans is on

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XWC experienced a UN1993 Resolv EC2472A release from a 330-gallon metal tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-tablespoon of product released to the tote body due to the tote cap not being sealed correctly. The crew re-secured the tote and preformed a slosh test to ensure no further release would occur in transit. The tote was wiped down and all impacted rags were placed into a 5-gallon metal pail. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On August 22, 2023, fifteen (15) one-gallon pails of UN1263 were crushed in transit and released approximately eight (8) gallons of product to the trailer interior, dock floor, and pavement beneath the trailer. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Lone Star Hazmat (LSH) to remediate the impacted site. LSH personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted areas and swept them in using hand tools. The crew then removed all impacted cardboard and plywood debris from the trailer. All clean up material was containerized in one (1) 55-gallon drum. The fifteen (15) damaged one-gallon pails were placed in one (1) additional 55-gallon drum. Borth drums were left onsite for further evaluation.

On August 22, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN3260 was damaged by a load shift and released approximately one (1) gallon of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. FCE personnel utilized hand tools and a HEPA shop vacuum to collect the free standing product from the trailer floor The crew then utilized degreasing agent with absorbent wipes to collect any residual product. All UN3260-impacted material was collected and containerized in one 91) 55-gallon drum for disposal by R+L.

column168: On August 23, 2023, one (1) 15-gallon drum of UN3267 was damaged due to a faulty skid and released approximately two (2) gallons of product to the trailer interior and pavement underneath the trailer. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Boston Green Company BCG to remediate the impacted site.  BCG personnel deployed neutralizing, granular absorbents to the corrosive-liquid impacted trailer and pavement and swept them in with hand tools. Crews also used hand tools to cut up the impacted pallet. BCG personnel proceeded to use a Hudson sprayer to wash down the trailer and pavement and deployed another layer of absorbents to ensure no product or product-rinseate remained at the site. All spent absorbents, the cut-up pallet, and miscellaneous cleanup debris were collected and containerized into two (2) 55-gallon poly drums.
